# lit Best Practices

This document serves as a definitive guide for using Lit effectively in your projects. Follow these best practices to ensure clean, efficient, and maintainable code.

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use Separate Files for Logic and Templates

❌ BAD
```javascript
class MyComponent extends LitElement {
  render() {
    return html`<div>${this.someMethod()}</div>`;
  }

  someMethod() {
    return 'Hello World';
  }
}
```

✅ GOOD
```javascript
// my-component.ts
export function getGreeting() {
  return 'Hello World';
}

// my-component.js
import { LitElement, html } from 'lit';
import { getGreeting } from './my-component.ts';

class MyComponent extends LitElement {
  render() {
    return html`<div>${getGreeting()}</div>`;
  }
}
```
**Why:** Keeping business logic separate from templates improves readability and maintainability.

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Use Properties and State Correctly

❌ BAD
```javascript
class MyComponent extends LitElement {
  @state() count = 0;

  increment() {
    this.count++;
  }
}
```

✅ GOOD
```javascript
class MyComponent extends LitElement {
  @property({ type: Number }) count = 0;

  increment() {
    this.count++;
  }
}
```
**Why:** Use `@property` for public APIs to ensure they are reactive. Use `@state` only for internal state management.

## Performance Considerations

### Optimize Rendering with Lifecycle Methods

❌ BAD
```javascript
class MyComponent extends LitElement {
  updated(changedProperties) {
    if (changedProperties.has('count')) {
      this.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('count-changed'));
    }
  }
}
```

✅ GOOD
```javascript
class MyComponent extends LitElement {
  async updated(changedProperties) {
    if (changedProperties.has('count')) {
      await this.updateComplete; // Ensure DOM is updated
      this.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('count-changed'));
    }
  }
}
```
**Why:** Always await `this.updateComplete` before dispatching events that rely on the rendered DOM to avoid inconsistencies.

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Avoid Browser-Specific APIs in SSR

❌ BAD
```javascript
class MyComponent extends LitElement {
  updated() {
    console.log(window.innerWidth); // Direct access to window
  }
}
```

✅ GOOD
```javascript
class MyComponent extends LitElement {
  updated() {
    if (typeof window !== 'undefined') {
      console.log(window.innerWidth); // Guard against SSR
    }
  }
}
```
**Why:** Ensure compatibility with server-side rendering by checking for browser-specific APIs.

## Component Architecture

### Favor Composition Over Inheritance

❌ BAD
```javascript
class BaseComponent extends LitElement {
  // Base functionality
}

class MyComponent extends BaseComponent {
  // Inherits from BaseComponent
}
```

✅ GOOD
```javascript
class MyComponent extends LitElement {
  render() {
    return html`<my-other-component></my-other-component>`;
  }
}
```
**Why:** Component composition leads to more flexible and reusable components compared to inheritance.

## State Management

### Use the Mediator Pattern for Peer Communication

❌ BAD
```javascript
class ParentComponent extends LitElement {
  handleChildEvent(event) {
    this.childComponent.someMethod();
  }
}
```

✅ GOOD
```javascript
class ParentComponent extends LitElement {
  connectedCallback() {
    super.connectedCallback();
    this.addEventListener('child-event', this.handleChildEvent.bind(this));
  }

  handleChildEvent(event) {
    // Handle event
  }
}
```
**Why:** Use events to communicate between components, promoting decoupling and reusability.

## Accessibility

### Ensure ARIA Roles and Attributes are Set

❌ BAD
```javascript
class MyComponent extends LitElement {
  render() {
    return html`<button>${this.label}</button>`;
  }
}
```

✅ GOOD
```javascript
class MyComponent extends LitElement {
  render() {
    return html`<button aria-label="${this.label}">${this.label}</button>`;
  }
}
```
**Why:** Always use ARIA roles and attributes to enhance accessibility for assistive technologies.

## Testing Approaches

### Use Lit Testing Utilities

❌ BAD
```javascript
import { html } from 'lit';
import { expect } from 'chai';

describe('MyComponent', () => {
  it('renders correctly', () => {
    const el = new MyComponent();
    document.body.appendChild(el);
    expect(el.shadowRoot.querySelector('button').textContent).to.equal('Click me');
  });
});
```

✅ GOOD
```javascript
import { html, fixture, expect } from '@open-wc/testing';

describe('MyComponent', () => {
  it('renders correctly', async () => {
    const el = await fixture(html`<my-component></my-component>`);
    expect(el.shadowRoot.querySelector('button').textContent).to.equal('Click me');
  });
});
```
**Why:** Use the testing utilities from the Lit ecosystem to simplify your tests and ensure they are reliable.

By following these guidelines, you will create robust, maintainable, and performant Lit components that adhere to modern best practices. Always remember to keep your code clean, organized, and accessible.